  "prompt": "Why is mercury in a thermometer red?",
  "response": "Mercury in a thermometer is not actually red; it is a silvery, metallic liquid. However, confusion often arises because there are other types of thermometers that contain red liquid, which is usually alcohol-based and dyed red or another color for visibility. These alcohol thermometers are commonly used as a safer alternative to mercury thermometers, which can be hazardous if broken.\n\nMercury thermometers are now less common due to the health and environmental risks associated with mercury exposure. The shift toward using colored alcohol or other non-toxic liquids makes thermometers more user-friendly and safer.",
